West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Jaundrill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jaundrill","meanings":["Norman, English: nickname from Middle English * <i>jaunerel</i> ( <i>jaune</i> ‘yellow’ + suffix  <i>-erel</i>, of Anglo-Norman origin), for someone with a yellowish complexion, possibly suffering from jaundice. For the  <i>-d-</i>, compare the word  <i>jaundice</i>, from Old French  <i>jaunice</i>. The variant  <i>Jod(e)rell</i> may have arisen through misreading  <i>Jandrell</i> as * <i>Jaudrell</i>. Note William Jawdrell, 1448 in PROB 11, whose name may be an early form of  <i>Jodrell</i> or a misreading of  <i>Jaundrell</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Jodrell was born in 1341, in England, his father, Roger Jaudrell, was 33 and his mother, Martha, was 30. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Agnes DeBradshaw. He died in 1375, in his hometown, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1341–1375":"1341–1375","1336–1357":"1336–1357","1343–Female":"1343–Surnud","1361–Male":"1361–Surnud","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1371–1423":"1371–1423","1309–1350":"1309–1350","1311–Female":"1311–Surnud","1341":"1341","1350":"1350","1361":"1361","1371":"1371","1336":"1336","1423":"1423","1357":"1357","1311":"1311","1365"